==English==
===Etymology===
{{L.}} [[jus]], ''[[law]]'' + [[cogens]] from [[cogere]], ''to [[compel]]''
===Noun phrase===
{{wikipediapar|peremptory norm}}
'''jus cogens'''
#{{law}} a [[constraining]] [[law]] or [[peremptory]] [[norm]]; a [[fundamental]] [[principle]] of [[international law]] considered to be accepted by all states.

See Chapter IV of the Emerging System of International Criminal Law: Developments in Codification and Implementation (1997) [[Lyal Sunga | Lyal S. Sunga]] on "Advent of Normative Hierarchy in International Law   and its Relation to Individual Criminal Responsibility" pages 229-248, discussing the relation among jus cogens, obligations erga omnes and 'international crimes of State' as well as the relation of these concepts to normative hierarchy in international law and individual criminal responsibility.